<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n17051b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n17" href="#n17051b">N17 (VI.B.9)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n17all.htm#n17051b"> 51(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a pipe of chalk</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">When gravel overlies chalk, in eastern and southern England, a pit or cutting often displays the former <font color="green">[chemical action of rain]</font> filling a kind of shaft or pouch in the latter <font color="green">[mechanical action]</font>. These are called <mark>sand-pipes</mark>, and above one of them, the gravel which elsewhere is distinctly stratified has completely lost that structure, the positions of the fragments sometimes even suggesting a downward movement. <small> T.G. Bonney, <a name="RAIN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RAIN"><cite title="source">The Work of Rain and Rivers</cite></a> (1923) 10</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
